==English==

===Etymology===
From {{prefix|re|cast|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|rē-käst'}}, {{IPA|/riːˈkɑːst/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ɑːst|lang=en}}
* {{enPR|rē-kăst'}}, {{IPA|/riːˈkæst/|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|æst|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|recasts|recasting|recast}}

# To [[cast]] or [[throw]] again.
#* {{RQ:Flr Mntgn Essays}}, I.47:
#*: the Roman gentlemen armed at all assayes, in the middest of their running-race, would cast and '''recast''' themselves from one to another horse.
# To [[mould]] [[again]].
#: ''The whole bell had to be '''recast''' although it had only one tiny, hardly visible crack.''
# To reproduce in a new [[form]].
#* '''1999''', Joyce Crick, translating Sigmund Freud, ''The Interpretation of Dreams'', Oxford 2008, p.33:
#*: Our conception of the world rises in us as our intellect '''recasts''' {{transterm|umgiesst|lang=de}} the impressions it receives from without into the forms of time, space, and causality.

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The act or process of recasting.
# {{context|linguistics|lang=en}} An [[utterance]] translated into another [[grammatical]] form.
#: ''Adults may use '''recasts''' to suggest corrections to mistakes in children's speech.''

